'getParcelable(String?): T?' is deprecated. Deprecated in Java

override fun onActivityResult(requestCode: Int, resultCode: Int, data: Intent?) {
        super.onActivityResult(requestCode, resultCode, data)

        if (requestCode == requestImageCapture && resultCode == Activity.RESULT_OK) {
            val imageBitmap = data?.extras?.getParcelable("data") as? Bitmap
            val imageView: ImageView = findViewById(R.id.image_layout)
            imageView.setImageBitmap(imageBitmap)
        }
    }

The deprecation of `getParcelable(String?)` method in Android is part of a broader push to encourage developers to adopt more modern and safer coding practices. With advancements in Android SDK, including improved type safety and null handling, newer APIs have been introduced. To handle the deprecation and use a more type-safe approach to extract `Parcelable` objects from Intent extras, you can use the `getParcelableExtra` method with the correct type specified. 

Here's how you can update the `onActivityResult` method to adhere to the new practices:

```java
@Override
protected void onActivityResult(int requestCode, int resultCode, Intent data) {
    super.onActivityResult(requestCode, resultCode, data);

    if (requestCode == requestImageCapture && resultCode == Activity.RESULT_OK) {
        if (data != null && data.getExtras() != null) {
            Bitmap imageBitmap = data.getExtras().getParcelable("data");
            ImageView imageView = findViewById(R.id.image_layout);
            imageView.setImageBitmap(imageBitmap);
        }
    }
}
```

For Android API level 33 and above, as part of Android 13 (Tiramisu) changes, you might prefer using the more specific type-safe method `getParcelableExtra(T::class.java.name)`, particularly if targeting the latest SDK version. Given that the method `getParcelable` expects a string key and returns a `Parcelable`, the direct replacement is `getParcelableExtra`, which also requires specifying the class of the expected return type explicitly.

However, the code snippet provided is already using the `getParcelable` method in a way that doesn't directly raise the deprecation issue highlighted. If you're facing issues or warnings regarding deprecation, ensure your development environment targets the appropriate Android SDK version and follows the latest practices recommended by Android documentation.

Also, always make sure to check the official Android developer documentation or the Android Developers website for the most recent and recommended approaches, especially as new Android versions are released and development practices evolve.

